(c) Two passages in the philosophical treatises of 13.C. 44, viz. de Amic. 5 29 and de Senect. 5 69, read as though they were expansions of sentences in pro Marc. 5 9 and 5 ²7 respectively. The impugners of the speech have made a great deal of them: as though the parallelism could only be explained by deliberate transcription, and not by unconscious sels—repetition. In the same way the coincidences of language with the Letters of the period (especially ad Fam. iv. 4) have been cited to prove that the pro Marcello is a sort of cento of Ciceronian sentences, a declamatio written by some student in the schools of the early Empire‚ and redolent of their rhetoric and philosophy.
